restricted to a single
trusted IP
HTTP TCP 80 0.0.0.0/0 Public web access
HTTPS TCP 443 0.0.0.0/0 Secure public web
access
Outbound rules left at the default (all traffic, 0.0.0.0/0) so the instance can reach package repositories, CloudWatch, and
S3 — outbound restriction wasn’t necessary for this workload, and the risk of leaving it open is low compared to inbound
exposure.
Identity — IAM
Created a dedicated IAM role, devops-ec2-role , attached directly to the EC2 instance (no long-lived access keys
stored on the server).
Only two policies attached:
CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy — lets the instance publish metrics and logs.
AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess — lets the instance read from S3, but never write or delete.
No IAM user credentials are embedded anywhere in code or configuration — the EC2 instance assumes the role
automatically via its instance profile.
Secrets management
EC2 host, username, and SSH private key are stored as GitHub Secrets, not in the repository or workflow file.
The .pem private key is never committed to Git and never printed in workflow logs.
Data protection
S3 bucket has Block all public access enabled (all four settings on) — the backup bucket cannot be reached from
the public internet.
Summary of least-privilege principle applied
Area Control
Network Only 3 inbound ports open, SSH locked to a single IP
